- ...family of means,
and she used her power

00:00:13.470 --> 00:00:16.830
to set up a facility
that served, initially,

00:00:16.830 --> 00:00:20.020
people with developmental disabilities.

00:00:20.020 --> 00:00:22.550
I'm gonna show you, oh
first I have to say,

00:00:22.550 --> 00:00:27.550
I have nothing to disclose,
this is a legal thing here,

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:31.520
but this is a, what you
see here is a photo,

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:33.860
it's kinda hard to make
out, but down at the bottom,

00:00:33.860 --> 00:00:37.610
this is a photo of the
coast at San Francisco

00:00:37.610 --> 00:00:40.050
many years ago, and there was a pool.

00:00:40.050 --> 00:00:41.770
It was at that time, and probably,

00:00:41.770 --> 00:00:43.610
if it was still in
existence, would still be

00:00:43.610 --> 00:00:46.640
the largest outdoor pool in the world.

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:48.870
It was, it used ocean water.

00:00:48.870 --> 00:00:51.950
If you could imagine
the coast of this city

00:00:51.950 --> 00:00:54.910
pumping ocean water into a pool,

00:00:54.910 --> 00:00:58.800
that was more than three
football fields long.

00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:03.800
The lifeguards had to sit in
canoes to patrol the pool.

00:01:04.410 --> 00:01:06.850
But the Pomeroy Center was founded,

00:01:06.850 --> 00:01:10.050
as was mentioned, as the
rec center initially.

00:01:10.050 --> 00:01:14.630
And right behind the pool
was the San Francisco Zoo,

00:01:14.630 --> 00:01:16.670
so I guess at that time, where did

00:01:16.670 --> 00:01:17.930
people with disabilities go?

00:01:17.930 --> 00:01:20.049
Well they went to right behind the zoo

00:01:20.049 --> 00:01:23.820
and into a building at a
pool that was very cold,

00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:26.450
and they were on an upper
floor of the rec center.

00:01:26.450 --> 00:01:29.270
So, you know, if you had mobility issues,

00:01:29.270 --> 00:01:31.530
you, I guess you were
carried up the stairs,

00:01:31.530 --> 00:01:36.530
there was no way to get up there.

00:01:36.530 --> 00:01:39.638
But, nonetheless, Janet
Pomeroy used her position

00:01:39.638 --> 00:01:44.420
to wrangle from the city the space

00:01:44.420 --> 00:01:47.480
to open up a rec center,
and the purpose was

00:01:47.480 --> 00:01:50.630
so that families did not have to leave

00:01:50.630 --> 00:01:52.850
children that had
developmental disabilities

00:01:52.850 --> 00:01:55.440
at home all day, but instead had a place

00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:57.510
where they could go, and at least

00:01:57.510 --> 00:01:59.693
have recreational activities.

00:02:00.730 --> 00:02:03.490
Later on, and there's
piece of land towards

00:02:03.490 --> 00:02:05.710
the back of that picture,
it's just all wooded,

00:02:05.710 --> 00:02:08.790
the city agreed to give
her that space too.

00:02:08.790 --> 00:02:11.180
It's about a five acre plot of land,

00:02:11.180 --> 00:02:13.550
which we are still on,
as long as she could

00:02:13.550 --> 00:02:16.000
come up with the money to develop it.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.100
You know at that time, it would be really

00:02:18.100 --> 00:02:20.010
hard to get five acres
from the city today,

00:02:20.010 --> 00:02:23.493
but at that time, she was able to do it.

00:02:24.600 --> 00:02:27.690
And what's really
interesting about that is

00:02:27.690 --> 00:02:31.190
her, in her mind, when she set that up,

00:02:31.190 --> 00:02:33.470
she didn't want it to be just a place for

00:02:33.470 --> 00:02:35.510
people with disabilities,
but she wanted it

00:02:35.510 --> 00:02:37.790
to be a community center.

00:02:37.790 --> 00:02:39.960
A place where people could come

00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:44.120
and people who don't have
disabilities could come as well.

00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:47.030
And you're gonna see
in the next few slides,

00:02:47.030 --> 00:02:52.030
some of what's going on
in Pomeroy Center today.

00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:54.980
I do want to let everybody know that,

00:02:54.980 --> 00:02:57.610
like any other day program that serves

00:02:57.610 --> 00:03:00.310
people with disabilities, we are licensed.

00:03:00.310 --> 00:03:04.200
We do hold a platinum seal of transparency

00:03:04.200 --> 00:03:07.305
from GuideStar, and we also recently

00:03:07.305 --> 00:03:10.240
received another three year accreditation

00:03:11.202 --> 00:03:12.150
from the Commission on Accreditation

00:03:12.150 --> 00:03:14.643
and Rehabilitation Facilities.

00:03:17.380 --> 00:03:20.480
Right now, and I'm gonna talk about

00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:23.470
the current goals at the Pomeroy Center,

00:03:23.470 --> 00:03:24.530
and then I'm gonna talk a little bit

00:03:24.530 --> 00:03:29.530
about what we aspire to
be in the future as well.

00:03:30.120 --> 00:03:34.010
So right now we are continuing to strive

00:03:34.010 --> 00:03:36.780
to become a compelling community center

00:03:36.780 --> 00:03:39.950
that serves a diverse population.

00:03:39.950 --> 00:03:42.750
This is a part of our population.

00:03:42.750 --> 00:03:46.430
Every day, we have a program for children,

00:03:46.430 --> 00:03:48.810
the only after school program for kids

00:03:48.810 --> 00:03:52.200
with special needs in the
city of San Francisco.

00:03:52.200 --> 00:03:54.420
And although it looks
like the buses never end,

00:03:54.420 --> 00:03:57.740
I mean some days it feels like that,

00:03:57.740 --> 00:04:00.990
every day we get about 80 kids

00:04:00.990 --> 00:04:03.333
that come from the school district,

00:04:03.333 --> 00:04:07.570
public schools into our
center between 2:30 and 3:00,

00:04:07.570 --> 00:04:09.960
and at just about the time
when most of the staff's

00:04:09.960 --> 00:04:13.500
sort of winding down, looking
for that last cup of coffee,

00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:18.150
all these kids come in and the
energy level really goes up.

