00:08:06.050 --> 00:08:09.727
Um, we have another, there's
another part of our program

00:08:09.727 --> 00:08:12.290
that's very important
to the Pomeroy Center

00:08:12.290 --> 00:08:14.230
in terms of bringing the public in,

00:08:14.230 --> 00:08:17.070
and that's this warm water pool.

00:08:17.070 --> 00:08:21.630
So, as our program was built,
you know, it has its roots

00:08:21.630 --> 00:08:24.717
as a recreational center,
and certainly the pool.

00:08:24.717 --> 00:08:28.830
And Janet wanted the pool to be created.

00:08:28.830 --> 00:08:30.660
It's warm water, what I mean by warm water

00:08:30.660 --> 00:08:33.400
we keep it between 92 and 94 degrees.

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:35.690
It's salt water based, like the ocean,

00:08:35.690 --> 00:08:38.340
except it's a little
bit, we make the salt's

00:08:38.340 --> 00:08:40.580
a little bit better for your skin.

00:08:40.580 --> 00:08:44.660
And the pool's used by
adults from the community

00:08:44.660 --> 00:08:46.350
in both the morning and the evening,

00:08:46.350 --> 00:08:48.110
people that may have had surgery

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:52.510
or they have some issue
of pain that they're

00:08:52.510 --> 00:08:55.650
trying to solve or they're
rehabilitating themselves,

00:08:55.650 --> 00:08:57.810
and the pool's fantastic for that.

00:08:57.810 --> 00:09:02.180
It's also in mid morning
and right after school,

00:09:02.180 --> 00:09:04.600
we have infant swimming lessons and then

00:09:04.600 --> 00:09:06.400
children's swimming lessons.

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:09.260
It's the best place in the
world if you have a baby,

00:09:09.260 --> 00:09:11.313
because the water is like bath water.

00:09:11.313 --> 00:09:14.070
You never hear an infant
scream like you do

00:09:14.070 --> 00:09:15.560
when you go to the Y and they dip 'em

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:17.660
in the cold pool and they're freaking out.

00:09:17.660 --> 00:09:21.180
That just does not happen
at the Pomeroy Center.

00:09:21.180 --> 00:09:24.880
And so we, the pool is
a very important part

00:09:24.880 --> 00:09:26.330
of bringing the community in.

00:09:27.210 --> 00:09:30.600
The other goal we have is
to help our participants

00:09:30.600 --> 00:09:33.860
demonstrate their value,
not only by working

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:36.620
but also volunteering in the community.

00:09:36.620 --> 00:09:41.060
So we serve about 250
adults and more than 100

00:09:41.060 --> 00:09:43.830
of them are not verbal,
or their verbal skills

00:09:43.830 --> 00:09:45.400
are very very minimal.

00:09:45.400 --> 00:09:48.888
Some of them, a number of
them are not verbal or vocal.

00:09:48.888 --> 00:09:53.888
And so it is a very,
very difficult population

00:09:55.220 --> 00:09:57.490
to get into the work community.

00:09:57.490 --> 00:09:59.790
But that doesn't mean
they don't have value.

00:09:59.790 --> 00:10:03.950
So we have found ways of
helping our participants

00:10:03.950 --> 00:10:07.350
get into the community by
volunteering to do things.

00:10:07.350 --> 00:10:11.290
This is a group here that
works with the food bank.

00:10:11.290 --> 00:10:13.760
Every Tuesday we get a pallet of food

00:10:13.760 --> 00:10:17.000
from the San Francisco Marin food bank.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:19.510
We separate it into grocery bags.

00:10:19.510 --> 00:10:22.100
Our participants, we load them up in a van

00:10:22.100 --> 00:10:24.700
and all the groceries,
and we deliver groceries

00:10:24.700 --> 00:10:27.960
to needy people in San Francisco.

00:10:27.960 --> 00:10:30.250
And I will tell you,
like the two gentlemen

00:10:30.250 --> 00:10:32.909
on the right, neither one is verbal,

00:10:32.909 --> 00:10:37.330
but when the van pulls up, they recognize

00:10:37.330 --> 00:10:39.120
the apartment building they're going into,

00:10:39.120 --> 00:10:40.940
they know the apartment they're going to,

00:10:40.940 --> 00:10:43.230
they knock on the door, they go in,

00:10:43.230 --> 00:10:45.480
they feel very valuable and valued

00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:48.500
by the community to do that.

00:10:48.500 --> 00:10:51.180
This is a group of the able gardeners.

00:10:51.180 --> 00:10:52.680
You're seeing them in the background,

00:10:52.680 --> 00:10:55.400
you see downtown San Francisco,

00:10:55.400 --> 00:10:57.963
just out in the community doing a project.

00:10:59.750 --> 00:11:01.550
This is our food bank volunteers.

00:11:01.550 --> 00:11:03.530
We also, besides delivering groceries,

00:11:03.530 --> 00:11:06.770
work at the food bank to help them sort

00:11:06.770 --> 00:11:08.720
their incoming food to get it ready

00:11:08.720 --> 00:11:11.753
to go out to other organizations.

00:11:12.810 --> 00:11:17.070
We also deliver meals for
Meals on Wheels in the city.

00:11:17.070 --> 00:11:20.410
So this is another
nonprofit that we work with.

00:11:20.410 --> 00:11:23.260
And just like the food bank, on Wednesdays

00:11:23.260 --> 00:11:27.230
right now, we load up
our van and we take food

00:11:27.230 --> 00:11:31.400
right now to 36 needy families
throughout San Francisco.

00:11:31.400 --> 00:11:33.780
And the director of the
food bank just contacted me

00:11:33.780 --> 00:11:36.420
today about adding another route.

00:11:36.420 --> 00:11:39.370
I was assured that this
selfie was not taken

00:11:39.370 --> 00:11:41.557
while the van was in
motion (audience laughing).

00:11:44.095 --> 00:11:45.195
I have no way to know.

00:11:48.360 --> 00:11:52.930
In our program, we also have
a full size basketball gym.

00:11:52.930 --> 00:11:56.130
And this is a group of our participants

00:11:56.130 --> 00:12:00.370
practicing basketball, but our team,

