And he is in great
health and great spirits,

00:12:58.380 --> 00:12:59.793
and he loves to golf.

00:13:01.040 --> 00:13:04.320
Last thing we're working
on right now of big issues

00:13:04.320 --> 00:13:06.820
are our expressive arts program.

00:13:06.820 --> 00:13:10.670
And we want, it is amazing,
and I know some of you

00:13:10.670 --> 00:13:13.680
are probably familiar
with this, but everyone

00:13:13.680 --> 00:13:16.410
has an ability to express themselves.

00:13:16.410 --> 00:13:19.120
Sometimes verbally they don't,

00:13:19.120 --> 00:13:20.810
that's not how they do it,

00:13:20.810 --> 00:13:22.580
but they can do it through art,

00:13:22.580 --> 00:13:24.440
or they can do it through music.

00:13:24.440 --> 00:13:27.150
We have an amazing art program,

00:13:27.150 --> 00:13:30.000
and our artists show their art

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.830
at bakeries in the city,
we have a couple of retail

00:13:33.830 --> 00:13:36.000
locations where we sell our art,

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.840
and they of course we have
the Pomeroy Center itself.

00:13:38.840 --> 00:13:41.830
And the art class is one of the classes

00:13:41.830 --> 00:13:46.720
that the City College of San
Francisco professors run.

00:13:46.720 --> 00:13:48.880
And so they're not only teaching,

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:52.190
but opening it up for the community.

00:13:52.190 --> 00:13:53.730
And all kinds of art.

00:13:53.730 --> 00:13:57.550
I mean we saw some painting,
we also do a lot of sculpture,

00:13:57.550 --> 00:14:01.900
and then we do an expressive
art through music as well.

00:14:01.900 --> 00:14:06.380
And as well as dance, so I
showed you the dance studio,

00:14:06.380 --> 00:14:10.320
one of our staff, the
woman on the far left,

00:14:12.469 --> 00:14:14.480
she came to us, she's
a director of a staff.

00:14:14.480 --> 00:14:18.150
But in the evening, after
work, she's a ballerina

00:14:18.150 --> 00:14:19.390
here in San Francisco.

00:14:19.390 --> 00:14:23.210
So she brought her talent
to the Pomeroy Center

00:14:23.210 --> 00:14:27.570
so after providing direct
service, or as part of that,

00:14:27.570 --> 00:14:31.220
she also teaches a dance
class, and this is just part

00:14:31.220 --> 00:14:35.053
of a performance they put on
during the holiday season.

00:14:38.090 --> 00:14:39.710
And this is our drama class.

00:14:39.710 --> 00:14:42.880
And they meet Tuesdays
and Thursday nights.

00:14:42.880 --> 00:14:45.750
And again, a lot of self expression

00:14:45.750 --> 00:14:48.490
and a lot of ability for people to really

00:14:48.490 --> 00:14:51.030
get up and do something
that they really wanna do

00:14:51.030 --> 00:14:56.030
in front of their peers and in
front of an audience as well.

00:14:56.070 --> 00:14:59.523
Wonderful woman there,
Hope, with her tambourine.

00:15:00.870 --> 00:15:02.337
The last goal we've been working on,

00:15:02.337 --> 00:15:05.870
and this is a lot of work for us,

00:15:05.870 --> 00:15:09.375
and that's because of
our children's program.

00:15:09.375 --> 00:15:13.410
So we have right now 82
kids in that program.

00:15:13.410 --> 00:15:16.760
70 of them have autism as either one

00:15:16.760 --> 00:15:19.500
or part of a dual diagnosis.

00:15:19.500 --> 00:15:23.143
It is an amazing number
when you think about that.

00:15:24.160 --> 00:15:28.070
And our children, you know
we have a big playground.

00:15:28.070 --> 00:15:30.120
Our kids program is six days a week.

00:15:30.120 --> 00:15:31.840
So we have an after school program

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:34.360
and then an all day Saturday program.

00:15:34.360 --> 00:15:35.960
And then when the public schools

00:15:36.897 --> 00:15:38.850
are closed, we're open and we have camp.

00:15:38.850 --> 00:15:41.040
So parents have an opportunity

00:15:41.040 --> 00:15:44.233
to continue to have
their children come in.

00:15:45.260 --> 00:15:49.950
We keep a 1:4 ratio, staff to children.

00:15:49.950 --> 00:15:53.670
And, you know, the kids are
just, they're just great.

00:15:53.670 --> 00:15:56.720
We have, this is what's
called a Snoezelen room.

00:15:56.720 --> 00:15:58.680
That's not a name we made up, by the way,

00:15:58.680 --> 00:16:00.630
it's actually a scientific name.

00:16:00.630 --> 00:16:02.230
But it's a sensory room.

00:16:02.230 --> 00:16:05.830
It doesn't do justice to
look at it in a static way,

00:16:05.830 --> 00:16:08.540
but there's a lot of motion in the room.

00:16:08.540 --> 00:16:10.500
There's videos going on of things

00:16:10.500 --> 00:16:13.790
that are very calming,
there's lot of light sensory.

00:16:13.790 --> 00:16:16.300
There's some sound as well.

00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:19.610
There's chairs so people who are confined

00:16:19.610 --> 00:16:21.360
to wheelchairs can get out our their chair

00:16:21.360 --> 00:16:23.720
and sit in a hammock
or something different.

00:16:23.720 --> 00:16:25.410
We have very sophisticated tools

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:28.950
to transfer individuals
from one thing to another.

00:16:28.950 --> 00:16:32.500
So that everyone can
enjoy a different mode

00:16:32.500 --> 00:16:34.060
during the day, if they need it.

00:16:34.060 --> 00:16:37.380
Or, if they're in sensory overload,

00:16:37.380 --> 00:16:38.970
this is just a great place to relax.

00:16:38.970 --> 00:16:40.673
Where you find me most afternoons.

00:16:42.500 --> 00:16:47.270
Just more kids, bouncing
and Elizabeth, who,

00:16:47.270 --> 00:16:50.750
this is Elizabeth being
Elizabeth in our program.

00:16:50.750 --> 00:16:53.400
I wanna say, like everybody else,

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:58.400
I am amazed and just humbled by our staff

00:16:59.860 --> 00:17:04.400
because this is an extremely
expensive place to live.

00:17:04.400 --> 00:17:07.210
And we have to pay hourly wages to people

00:17:07.210 --> 00:17:09.240
who are taking care of
adults with disabilities,

00:17:09.240 --> 00:17:11.990
or children, and it's very difficult

00:17:11.990 --> 00:17:15.500
to live in the community
on what we are able to pay.

00:17:15.500 --> 00:17:19.370
But the staff, we have
very little turnover.

00:17:19.370 --> 00:17:22.813
And in the last two
years, we've had nobody

00:17:22.813 --> 00:17:26.960
go out and on unemployment insurance.

00:17:26.960 --> 00:17:31.680
You know, or leave us, you
know, it's just amazing to me.

00:17:31.680 --> 00:17:34.580
What are we trying to do moving forward?

00:17:34.580 --> 00:17:39.580
Well, one, we want to continue to have our

00:17:39.750 --> 00:17:44.300
individuals surpass their
community integration goals,

00:17:44.300 --> 00:17:47.490
either through employment
or volunteer service,

00:17:47.490 --> 00:17:50.200
combination of that, or
in any type of outing

00:17:50.200 --> 00:17:52.340
that would be meaningful to them.

00:17:52.340 --> 00:17:57.180
And I do want to say
that we do not set goals.

00:17:57.180 --> 00:17:58.930
A lot of people come in want to know

00:17:58.930 --> 00:18:02.000
what's your goal for number
of people to seek employment?

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.580
And I go, I don't have a goal for that.

00:18:04.580 --> 00:18:08.950
Our goal is to satisfy
our individuals' desires.

00:18:08.950 --> 00:18:11.310
And our goal to do that's 100%.

00:18:11.310 --> 00:18:13.160
But we don't put any other goal on it.

00:18:13.160 --> 00:18:16.950
It's all about what they
want out of their life,

00:18:16.950 --> 00:18:18.753
and what they want out of the program.

00:18:20.050 --> 00:18:23.420
We want our program to have an impact

00:18:23.420 --> 00:18:26.640
in this community, and
have that impact grow.

00:18:26.640 --> 00:18:28.560
So one of the things we're doing right now

00:18:28.560 --> 00:18:31.840
is we've just opened up
two residential facilities.

00:18:31.840 --> 00:18:34.584
That is not something
we've been in before.

00:18:34.584 --> 00:18:37.050
But it's something we
felt we had to go into

00:18:37.050 --> 00:18:41.020
because many group homes in
this city are being sold.

00:18:41.020 --> 00:18:42.570
People who've been running group homes,

00:18:42.570 --> 00:18:45.140
now hey my house can, I can get a million

00:18:45.140 --> 00:18:49.150
or two or three for my
home, and I can sell it

00:18:49.150 --> 00:18:51.600
and I can move to Redding
or I can move to Fresno

00:18:51.600 --> 00:18:53.560
or I can move out of state and start

00:18:53.560 --> 00:18:55.330
a group home somewhere else.

00:18:55.330 --> 00:18:58.540
And in San Francisco, housing
is a problem for everybody,

00:18:58.540 --> 00:19:00.890
but it's especially a problem for people

00:19:00.890 --> 00:19:02.340
with developmental disabilities.

00:19:02.340 --> 00:19:05.050
So we now have opened two group homes

00:19:05.050 --> 00:19:09.070
on Fulton Street, near
the Golden Gate Park.

00:19:09.070 --> 00:19:10.650
And they're just beautiful homes

00:19:10.650 --> 00:19:12.763
with a great, great vibe.

00:19:13.840 --> 00:19:15.780
The next thing we're looking at,

00:19:15.780 --> 00:19:18.620
because we have so much
experience with children,

00:19:18.620 --> 00:19:20.770
is having an integrated daycare program.

00:19:20.770 --> 00:19:24.740
So we're just about done
with our license for that,

00:19:24.740 --> 00:19:28.990
and we hope to serve 20
children in a daycare program,

00:19:28.990 --> 00:19:31.690
where at least half would be non-disabled

00:19:31.690 --> 00:19:36.270
public, paid spots, and the other would be

00:19:36.270 --> 00:19:37.870
kids with special needs that might be

00:19:37.870 --> 00:19:40.280
subsidized there, or not.

00:19:40.280 --> 00:19:43.700
But, the idea is that, and we've seen

00:19:43.700 --> 00:19:45.310
model after model that works.

00:19:45.310 --> 00:19:47.320
When you put kids together they do not

00:19:47.320 --> 00:19:49.630
detect disability at that age.

00:19:49.630 --> 00:19:51.630
They simply don't understand it.

00:19:51.630 --> 00:19:54.700
All they do is they look
for ways to get around it.

00:19:54.700 --> 00:19:57.990
They wanna include everybody
in the games that they play.

00:19:57.990 --> 00:20:01.930
And we think that that
mentality, starting at two

00:20:01.930 --> 00:20:04.950
and going to five years
old will carry over

00:20:04.950 --> 00:20:06.480
when these kids get into school,

00:20:06.480 --> 00:20:08.830
and when they get into the, eventually,

00:20:08.830 --> 00:20:11.280
into the employment market,

00:20:11.280 --> 00:20:13.080
because it won't be foreign to them.

00:20:14.840 --> 00:20:17.070
And I'm gonna end with just a couple

00:20:17.070 --> 00:20:20.730
of photos of some of our people.

00:20:20.730 --> 00:20:24.490
And then lastly, I just wanna say this.

00:20:24.490 --> 00:20:27.160
I know some of you, many
of you have probably

00:20:27.160 --> 00:20:32.160
have been to andadult day
program at one time or another.

00:20:32.270 --> 00:20:37.270
But when I walk into to our program,

00:20:38.630 --> 00:20:41.230
or really anyone, and you see

00:20:41.230 --> 00:20:46.230
in our case 250 adults, and
they just wanna be who they are.

00:20:49.160 --> 00:20:51.416
And somehow if you can just accept

00:20:51.416 --> 00:20:54.530
who they are, and the fact
that they have this value,

00:20:54.530 --> 00:20:57.180
and for some them, maybe the value is

00:20:57.180 --> 00:20:59.340
that they make you laugh,
and I know a lot of people

00:20:59.340 --> 00:21:00.350
that don't make me laugh.

00:21:00.350 --> 00:21:04.270
So, you know, they have this value

00:21:04.270 --> 00:21:07.680
that when you open your
mind and your heart to them,

00:21:07.680 --> 00:21:11.020
and then you learn how to
communicate, it's a struggle.

00:21:11.020 --> 00:21:13.640
You know, I grew up
learning how to communicate

00:21:13.640 --> 00:21:15.870
mostly verbally, a lot of the people

00:21:15.870 --> 00:21:19.590
I talk to now I can't use verbal cues

00:21:19.590 --> 00:21:21.640
to communicate with them.

00:21:21.640 --> 00:21:23.570
But when you find ways of communicating,

00:21:23.570 --> 00:21:25.690
it is amazing what you learn

00:21:25.690 --> 00:21:27.590
from these individuals every day.

00:21:27.590 --> 00:21:30.650
And for those of you not local,

00:21:30.650 --> 00:21:32.920
or those of you local,
if you're in the city,

00:21:32.920 --> 00:21:35.850
you're over by the zoo,
we're still by the zoo.

00:21:35.850 --> 00:21:38.220
Drop by, you're welcome any time.

00:21:38.220 --> 00:21:39.931
Thank you so much.

00:21:39.931 --> 00:21:42.181
(applause)

